I understand her desire to look "normal" and have what most consider to be a normal life...but from just the first couple of minutes it's obvious that her spirit is so incredibly bright and beautiful that even a paper bag on her head wouldn't change her. Such an inspiration, and to think that people are so entitled and feel as though their lives are the absolute worst because of petty, irrelevant reasons. Please keep that spirit, sweet girl. I have a feeling I'll be sharing your story to some of my patients next week. And it is so fortunate that you were able to receive such a generous donation. I had a patient pass just last week, and it was his wish to become a donor...unfortunately, when we called the organization after contacting and notifying his family, he was refused due to his previous histories. The man had been homeless prior to admission, and had been brought in through the ED unresponsive and with a fever. Though any infection he'd had had been resolved, and fever broken for over a week, he was still denied as a candidate for donation, both for science and research as well as for transplants for those in need. Though I understand the concern, as any recipient of a donated organ will be on immunosuppressants due to risk of rejection, it was incredibly heartbreaking. Even more so that his family members who shunned him when he was in need and would not answer any calls regarding the patient all showed up after his passing.

So someone loses their life, kindly and selflessly donate their face, and they give it to someone who tried to selfishly take their own life? My dad is in renal failure and waiting for a kidney... Did you know if you ever had a history of suicidal tendencies in the past that you cannot get a kidney transplant? We were surprised by that information too, the transplant team explained to us these donations are still rare. That the recipients need to be people who are expected to live long, happy and grateful lives. I'm happy to see that she doesn't want to kill herself now after her suicide backfired. I hope that she will not take this for granted. Having been suicidal myself in the past, a part of me feels like this should go to someone who was mutilated by abuse or in a car accident or a fire. The other side of me finds some kind of beauty in her awesome second chance. I just hope she really realizes how lucky she is and that she is obviously meant to be here.

Having read the article in Nat Geographic, I have to say, I'm incredibly conflicted by it all. The cynic in me questions why she out of hundreds of others, was given this opportunity, and it rather obviously boils down to age, and a lifelong commitment to being an experiment. Having shot herself in the face, I can't imagine how difficult the journey has been, for both Katie, and her family, but, what makes her story and more important than others? The psychiatrist seemed to be quite sure that Katie doesn't have suicidal thoughts, as she came to the conclusion that Katie hadn't pre meditated her suicide, but one has to consider, what is going to happen to this woman, five, ten years down the line?? All in all, I commend the surgeons, and Andrea's grandma for giving Katie a new chapter, I may be a cynic, but I can still see that at the end of the day, this was not solely a story about the miracles of science, but also the advancement of humanity; a welcome sight. I hope life treats you well Katie and that you succeed in all you wish.
